{
  "mitigation_currently_implemented": "Strict seccomp-bpf confinement for Splunkd (attempted)",
  "comments": "Attempted to constrain the Splunk agent (splunkd) on UbuntuComputer with a strict seccomp-bpf approach and an AppArmor-style confinement. The intent is to restrict the attack surface of the compromised host by blocking high-risk syscalls (e.g., tar/gzip/exec) and limiting Splunkd to only necessary filesystem paths and allowed network destinations. In this iteration, steps were attempted but not fully completed due to environment constraints (containerized Splunkd, missing paths, and tooling available in the sandbox). The mitigation remains valid and should be completed in the next pass (e.g., finalize a functional seccomp-bpf wrapper or a proper AppArmor profile, ensure the Splunk container/process is wrapped safely, and wire logging). If successful, these controls reduce the risk of further data staging and exfiltration from the compromised host while the attacker remains active.",
  "device_identifier": "UbuntuComputer",
  "commands": [
    "bash -lc 'cat > /etc/apparmor.d/usr.bin.splunkd <<\"EOF\"\\n#include <tunables/global>\\nprofile splunkd /usr/bin/splunkd {\\n  /usr/src/app/splunkd/** r,\\n  /usr/src/app/splunkd/** rwk,\\n  /var/log/splunk/** rwk,\\n  /etc/splunk/** r,\\n  /proc/** r,\\n  /sys/** r,\\n  /bin/sh ix,\\n  network inet stream,\\n}\\nEOF'",
    "bash -lc 'cat > /etc/secure-syscalls.json <<\"JSON\"\\n{\\n  \"allowed_syscalls\": [\"read\",\"write\",\"open\",\"close\",\"fstat\",\"mmap\"],\\n  \"denied_syscalls\": [\"tar\",\"gzip\",\"socket\",\"fork\",\"exec\"],\\n  \"shields\": {\"log\": true}\\n}\\nJSON'",
    "bash -lc 'cat > /etc/containers/selinux-policy.txt << \"TXT\"\\n# Placeholder: In this environment, we'll simulate a minimal seccomp-like policy via a script.\\nTXT'"
  ]
}

{
